            <div type="note" subtype="biographical">
                <head type="title"><persName corresp="#WEA">W. E. A. Axon</persName> (<date notBefore="1846" notAfter="1913">1846&#x2013;1913</date>)</head>
                <p>Among the first bibliographers of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <persName corresp="#WEA">William Edward Armytage Axon</persName> was a prolific and
                    wide&#x2010;ranging scholar. He worked at the <orgName corresp="#MANCHESTERFREELIBRARY">Manchester Free Library</orgName> and for
                    the <title type="periodical" corresp="#GUARDIAN_MANCHESTER"><hi rend="italic">Manchester Guardian</hi></title>, and he was active in numerous
                    organizations, including the <orgName corresp="#MANCHESTERLITERARYCLUB">Manchester Literary Club</orgName>. He contributed significantly to the study of local <placeName corresp="#LANCASHIRE">Lancashire</placeName> history and literature 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#AXONDNB"><persName corresp="#BCHOLLINGWORTH">Hollingworth</persName>, <title type="dictionary_entry" corresp="#AXONDNB">&#x201C;Axon&#x201D;</title></ref>).</p> 
                <p><persName corresp="#JC">John Carter</persName> lists <persName corresp="#WEA">Axon</persName> among &#x201C;that group of collectors which from the eighties onwards were concentrating on first editions of the Romantic 
                    and Victorian authors, and particularly on the poets&#x201D; 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#CARTERBOOKCOLLECTORS"><persName corresp="#JC">Carter</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#CARTERBOOKCOLLECTORS"><hi rend="italic">Books and Book&#x2010;Collectors</hi></title></ref>, 17).</p>
            </div>
